HOUSE BILL No. 1426
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
public safety.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 16-31-3-2, AS AMENDED BY P.L.139-2023,
2 SECTION 2, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 JANUARY 1, 2026 (RETROACTIVE)]: Sec. 2. The commission shall
4 establish standards for persons required to be certified or licensed by
5 the commission to provide emergency medical services. To be certified
6 or licensed, a person must meet the following minimum requirements:
7 (1) The personnel certified or licensed under this chapter must do
8 the following:
9 (A) Meet the standards for education and training established
10 by the commission by rule.
11 (B) Successfully complete a basic or an inservice course of
12 education and training on sudden infant death syndrome that
13 is certified by the commission in conjunction with the state
14 health commissioner.
15 (C) Successfully complete a basic or an inservice course of
16 education and training on autism that is certified by the
17 commission.
2026 IN 1426—LS 6809/DI 92

2
1 (D) Successfully complete a research based training program
2 concerning suicide assessment, treatment, and management
3 that is:
4 (i) demonstrated to be an effective or promising program;
5 and
6 (ii) recommended by the Indiana Suicide Prevention
7 Network Advisory Council.
8 (E) After December 31, 2024, complete basic training, which
9 may be completed online or by other means of virtual
10 instruction, that addresses the mental health and wellness of
11 persons required to be licensed under this chapter, including:
12 (i) healthy coping skills to preserve the mental health of
13 persons required to be licensed under this chapter and
14 manage the stress and trauma related to the provision of
15 emergency medical services;
16 (ii) recognition of symptoms of posttraumatic stress disorder
17 and signs of suicidal behavior; and
18 (iii) information on mental health resources available for
19 persons required to be licensed under this chapter.
20 (F) After December 31, 2025, successfully complete a basic
21 training, which may be completed online or by other
22 means of virtual instruction, on Alzheimer's disease and
23 dementia that is certified by the commission.
24 (2) Ambulances to be used must conform with the requirements
25 of the commission and must either be:
26 (A) covered by insurance issued by a company licensed to do
27 business in Indiana in the amounts and under the terms
28 required in rules adopted by the commission; or
29 (B) owned by a governmental entity covered under IC 34-13-3.
30 (3) Emergency ambulance service shall be provided in accordance
31 with rules adopted by the commission. However, the rules
32 adopted under this chapter may not prohibit the dispatch of an
33 ambulance to aid an emergency patient because an emergency
34 medical technician is not immediately available to staff the
35 ambulance.
36 (4) Ambulances must be equipped with a system of emergency
37 medical communications approved by the commission. The
38 emergency medical communication system must properly
39 integrate and coordinate appropriate local and state emergency
40 communications systems and reasonably available area
41 emergency medical facilities with the general public's need for
42 emergency medical services.
